# Templates

Imagine writing a `sum` function. You'd need one for `int`, one for `float`, one for `double`... Exhausting!

**Templates** allow you to write generic code that works with **any data type**.

```cpp
template <typename T>
T sum(T a, T b) {
    return a + b;
}
```
Now `sum(5, 10)` works, and `sum(5.5, 2.3)` also works!

# Generic Functions

The compiler automatically generates the correct function version based on the arguments you pass.

```cpp
template <typename T>
T getMax(T a, T b) {
    return (a > b) ? a : b;
}

int main() {
    cout << getMax(10, 20);      // T becomes int
    cout << getMax(3.14, 2.71);  // T becomes double
}
```

# Generic Classes

You can also make classes generic. Useful for data structures like stacks or queues.

```cpp
template <class T>
class Box {
    T value;
public:
    Box(T v) : value(v) {}
    T getValue() { return value; }
};

Box<int> intBox(10);
Box<string> strBox("Hello");
```
Note: You must specify the type `<int>` when creating the object.

# Navigating Containers 🧭

Iterators are objects that point to elements in a container.

```cpp
vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};
vector<int>::iterator it;

for(it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); it++) {
    cout << *it << " ";
}
```

Modern C++ (C++11) makes this easier with auto range loops:
`for(int x : v) cout << x;`

# Ready-made Logic 🧠

Include `<algorithm>` to accept the superpowers.

```cpp
#include <algorithm>

vector<int> v = {5, 1, 9, 3};

// Sorting
sort(v.begin(), v.end()); 
// v is now {1, 3, 5, 9}

// Finding
if (binary_search(v.begin(), v.end(), 5)) {
    cout << "Found 5!";
}
```

